Running a PyPy buildbot worker inside a container
=================================================

This is a fourth way to run a worker (see `README_BUILDSLAVE` for the others):
inside a prebuilt podman/docker image, using the images published by the
pypy-ci repo (`ghcr.io/pypy/buildworker_{x86_64,i686,aarch64}`).

The image ships the C build dependencies and a pinned PyPy2.7. The worker
itself runs in a virtualenv created on first start; `requirements.txt` in this
repo pins buildbot 0.8.8 and buildbot-slave.

There are two run scripts:

- `start-benchmarker2.sh` runs the benchmarker2 (x86_64) worker as root, as a service,
  pinned to a cpuset.
- `start-worker.sh` runs the other, rootless, command-line workers: `aarch64`,
  `linux-x86-64`, and `benchmarker2-32` (i686).

Setup on the host
------------------

Create the worker BASEDIR as described in `README_BUILDSLAVE` (the
`buildslave create-slave BASEDIR MASTERHOST:PORT SLAVENAME PASSWORD` step). Lay
it out so the container sees it and `requirements.txt`:

    $HOME/buildbot/
        slave/          # the created worker config (*.tac etc.)
        requirements.txt

The container maps your host UID straight through (`--userns=keep-id`), so
BASEDIR must be owned by you.

Each worker uses `slave/<TAC>`: the isolated workers use `buildbot.tac`, and
benchmarker2-32 uses `benchmarker2-32.tac` because it shares the slave
directory with the benchmarker2 worker.

Starting a worker
-----------------

    ./start-worker.sh aarch64
    ./start-worker.sh linux-x86-64
    ./start-worker.sh benchmarker2-32

The container name and its `/tmp/<worker>` scratch dir are named after the
worker, so the two workers sharing a slave directory never collide. The venv
lives in that `/tmp/<worker>` volume, so it survives restarts and is only built
the first time.

Per-worker specifics live in the `case` block in `start-worker.sh`: the image,
the tac file, and extra podman flags. benchmarker2-32 is a 32-bit image
(`--platform=linux/386`) and is colocated with the master (`--network=host`).

Stopping a worker
-----------------

    podman stop <worker-name>

`docker` can be substituted for `podman` throughout.
